04495nam a22006135i 9780292789685DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927896857 a10.7560/7124302doi  a(DE-B1597)587993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE840.8.Y3bC69 2001eb 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a328.73/0922221 aCox, Patrick L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRalph W. Yarborough, the People's Senator /cPatrick L. Cox. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 It Was a Joyous Boyhood -- t2 The Million-Dollar Victory -- t3 A Man Who Had to Earn His Way -- t4 The Hamburger Campaign -- t5 We Saw the Worst -- t6 The Strong Acid Test -- t7 Coonskins and Coon Hunters -- t8 Put the Jam on the Lower Shelf -- t9 Problems with Johnson and Rayburn -- t10 The Rancid Smell of Gunpowder -- t11 The Struggle for the Soul of the Nation -- t12 Acts of Congress and Acts of Madness -- t13 Final Senate Years and Election Defeat -- t14 The Last Hurrah -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRevered by many Texans and other Americans as "the People's Senator," Ralph Webster Yarborough (1903-1996) fought for "the little people" in a political career that places him in the ranks of the most influential leaders in Texas history. The only U. S. Senator representing a former Confederate state to vote for every significant piece of modern civil rights legislation, Yarborough became a cornerstone of Lyndon Johnson's Great Society programs in the areas of education, environmental preservation, and health care. In doing so, he played a major role in the social and economic modernization of Texas and the American South. He often defied conventional political wisdom with his stands against powerful political interests and with his vocal opposition to the Vietnam War. Yet to this day, his admirers speak of Yarborough as an inspiration for public service and a model of political independence and integrity. This biography offers the first in-depth look at the life and career of Ralph Yarborough. Patrick L. Cox draws on Yarborough's personal and professional papers, as well as on extensive interviews with the Senator and his associates, to follow Yarborough from his formative years in East Texas through his legal and judicial career in the 1930s, decorated military service in World War II, unsuccessful campaigns for Texas governor in the 1950s, distinguished tenure in the United States Senate from 1957 to 1970, and return to legal practice through the 1980s. Although Yarborough's liberal politics set him at odds with most of the Texas power brokers of his time, including Lyndon Johnson, his accomplishments have become part of the national fabric. Medicare recipients, beneficiaries of the Cold War G. I. Bill, and even beachcombers on Padre Island National Seashore all share in the lasting legacy of Senator Ralph Yarborough.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLegislatorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aKennedy, Edward M.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292789685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292789685/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK